{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=File:Tizian 085.jpg | artist=[[Titian]] | title=The Rape of Europa | year=ca. 1560-1562 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=178 | width_metric=205 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Boston]] | museum=[[Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum]] }} {{other uses|The Rape of Europa (disambiguation)}} '''''The Rape of Europa''''' is a painting by the Italian artist [[Titian]], painted ca. 1560-1562. It hangs in the [[Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum]] of [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]. The oil-on-canvas painting measures {{convert|178|x|205|cm}}.<ref name="museum">{{cite web | url=http://www.gardnermuseum.org/collection/artwork/3rd_floor/titian_room/europa | title=Europa | publisher=Isabells Stewart Gardner Museum | accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>
==Description== The title of the painting refers to the mythological story of the abduction of [[Europa (mythology)|Europa]] by [[Zeus]] ([[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] to the Romans),<ref name="museum" /> Titian is unequivocal about the fact that this is a scene of rape (abduction): Europa is sprawled helplessly on her back, her clothes in disarray.<ref>Stephen J. Campbell, "Europa," in Eye of the Beholder, edited by Alan Chong et al. (Boston: ISGM and Beacon Press, 2003): 103-107.</ref> In the myth, the god assumed the form of a bull and enticed Europa to climb onto his back. Once there, the bull rode into the sea and carried her to [[Crete]], where he revealed his real identity. Europa became the first Queen of Crete, and had three children with Zeus. The painting depicts Europa on the back of the bull, just off the shore of her homeland.
==Provenance== The painting was one of the "''poesie''" painted by Titian for [[Philip II of Spain]]. With [[Diana and Callisto (Titian)|''Diana and Callisto'']] and [[Diana and Actaeon (Titian)|''Diana and Actaeon'']], both now shared by London and Edinburgh, it was one of three Titian ''poesies'' given by [[Philip V of Spain]] to the French ambassador, the [[Antoine Charles IV de Gramont|Duke of Gramont]], who in turn presented them to [[Philippe II, Duke of Orléans]], Regent of France from 1715–1723.<ref>Brigstocke, Hugh; ''Italian and Spanish Paintings in the National Gallery of Scotland'', p. 183, 2nd Edn, 1993, National Galleries of Scotland, {{ISBN|0-903598-22-1}}</ref> For most of the 18th century it was in the [[Orleans Collection]] in Paris. It was purchased by [[Bernard Berenson]] on behalf of art collector [[Isabella Stewart Gardner]] in 1896.<ref>{{cite book|last=Saltzman|first=Cynthia|title=Old Masters, New World: America's Raid on Europe's Great Pictures, 1880-World War I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f8FQzgAL_aUC&pg=PA77|year=2008|publisher=Viking|isbn=978-0-670-01831-4|page=77}}</ref>
